# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-scab
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-scab/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apple-scab/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apple-scab/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apple-scab/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apple-scab/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apple-scab/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apple-scab/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apple-scab/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apple-scab/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apple-scab/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apple-scab/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apple-scab/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:apple-scab/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:apple-scab/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:apple-scab/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:apple-scab/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:apple-scab/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:apple-scab/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:apple-scab/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:apple-scab/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:apple-scab/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Its colour, juice content, sweetness, and overall flavour have made the Ambrosia one of the most purchased apples in numerous countries.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia apple tree has an upright growth pattern, varying on soil quality, rootstock, environment, and management.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] The tree develops lateral branches, requiring pruning to maintain vigour and fruit size.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] In the first two years of growth, significant tree training is needed to assure well-angled fruiting branches and productivity.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apple trees are suitable for dense planting, have high yields, and require little pruning during the winter.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Pollinating partners of the Ambrosia include the Cortland, Fuji, and Granny Smith.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] The fruit is medium to large, 6.8–7.5 cm (2.7–3.0 in) in diameter, weighing about 215 grams (0.474 lb), and has mostly red, glossy colouration, with yellow patches.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] It has cream-coloured, firm, and juicy texture, with a mild and sweet flavour reminiscent of pear and low acidity, with the flesh resisting oxidation, making it suitable for salads and fresh fruit displays.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] These apples flower in the mid-to-late blossom period, and are harvested in mid-to-late season (mid-September in its native Similkameen Valley of British Columbia; September–October in Ontario, mid-October in Quebec).
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apples produce a low amount of ethylene, not displaying the usual climacteric rise at harvest.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Accordingly, internal ethylene concentrations do not indicate accurate fruit maturity, whereas skin colour and starch staining charts are commonly used for optimal harvest and standardization of fruit quality.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Orchard irrigation conditions appear to be a factor causing soft scald and reduced quality of Ambrosia apples during storage.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Derived from a chance seedling, the Ambrosia is suspected to be a cross of the Starking Delicious and the Golden Delicious because those apples existed in the orchard where the Ambrosia was discovered growing.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is a "club" variety of apple, in which a cultivar is patented by an organization that sets quality standards and provides marketing, while production is limited to club members.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Centralized control allowed limitation of color variation to pink/red, as the variety would colour differently in warmer climates.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] The patent expired in Canada in 2015, in the United States in 2017, and in Chile in 2021.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] It remains active in many other countries until as late as 2034.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in Canada, the Mennell family obtained plant breeders rights, and all growers were allowed, paying a royalty of CA$2–3.75 per tree planting.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in the US, growers paid the lesser of US$1 per tree planting or US$1,000 per acre, and a US$1,000 franchise fee.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia Gold is marketed as the premium version of this variety.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is most commonly cultivated in British Columbia, where it was the third most-produced apple in 2016.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] By the mid 2020s, British Columbia continues to take the lead in production, followed by Ontario and Nova Scotia.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] Alongside the Honeycrisp and Gala, the Ambrosia has risen in prominence among Canadian farmers and consumers at the expense of the Red Delicious.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] In the United States, the majority of Ambrosia apples are harvested in Washington State and New York.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] This variety is also grown in Chile, New Zealand, the Netherlands, and Italy, among other countries.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] In the early 21st century, it is one of the most popular apple varieties in Canada and the United States, especially in the South and Midwest.
[src:apple-scab/ambrosia-apple] It has also found success in the Asian market, notably Vietnam.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] The earliest official reports of apple scab were made in 1819 by Swedish botanist, Elias Fries.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] However, genetic studies have indicated that apple scab likely emerged in Central Asia.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] As neither the spores nor conidia of this disease are capable of travelling great distances, it is likely that apple scab spread through the movement of domesticated apple trees by migrating humans.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] By the end of the 19th century, the disease had spread to North America and Oceania alongside the importation of host plants.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Today apple scab is present in nearly all regions where apples are cultivated, with the most significant infections occurring in temperate areas, where it is cool and moist in the spring.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] The disease cycle begins in early spring, when cool temperatures and abundant moisture promote the release of sexual spores (ascospores) from overwintering structures (pseudothecia) found in the debris at the base of previously infected trees.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Moisture is a critical factor in the development of the disease as rainfall not only triggers the release of ascospores, but also facilitates the infection of new hosts by helping the spores adhere to and germinate on the healthy tissue of new hosts.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Following their dissemination, ascospores are transported to the surfaces of newly emerged leaves and blossoms by wind and splashing water.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] The tissue is then penetrated either directly with a germ tube or indirectly using an appressorium, thus initiating a new infection.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Shortly after penetration, light-green, irregularly shaped lesions develop on infected foliar tissue and gradually darken, expand, and pucker as the infection progresses.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Lesions on fruit are black or brown and irregularly shaped, with older fruit lesions causing the underlying tissue to become dry, corky, and eventually disfigured by splitting.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Within 10 days of infection, asexual conidia will develop on the darkened lesions and allow for the establishment of secondary infections in healthy leaf and fruit tissue.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Under optimal conditions, this cycle may repeat every 1–2 weeks during the growing season.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] At the end of the season, heavily infected fruit and foliage fall from the canopy, allowing for the development of pseudothecia, which serve as a source of primary inoculum for the next spring.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] First developed in 1944 by American plant pathologist, W.D.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Mills, a Mills Table predicts the likelihood of an apple scab infection developing based on the average temperature and the number of hours of leaf wetness that the host plant is exposed to.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] This prediction system has been rapidly adopted in both Europe and North America, where apple growers use it as an early warning system for new infections, allowing them to apply preventive fungicides when appropriate.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Several revisions have been made to the Mills Table since its creation.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] The most notable revision was made in 1989 by plant pathologists William MacHardy and David Gadoury, who determined that ascospores required 3 hours less than originally calculated in order to establish a new infection.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] While other methods of prediction include ascospore maturation models and leaf orchard leaf canopy models, the Mills Table, combined with electronic weather monitoring, remains the most-widely used tool for predicting apple scab infection periods.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Cultural controls may be used as a first step when seeking to reduce the incidence of new infections.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] These practices include cleaning leaf litter from the base of previously infected trees, as well as removing infected woody material from the canopy when performing annual pruning.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Doing so will reduce the amount of primary inoculum in the spring and subsequently delay the establishment of the disease.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Furthermore, regular pruning will improve air flow and light penetration in the canopy, which ultimately inhibits the development and spread of disease.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Another aspect of cultural control is water management.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] As water triggers ascospore release and promotes germination on vulnerable tissue, growers are advised to monitor watering periods and avoid using overhead watering systems.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Doing so may ultimately aid in reducing infection periods caused by natural precipitation.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] The management of apple scab using chemical controls is primarily concerned with preventing the initiation of primary infection cycles by reducing the germination of ascospores.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] As such, fungicides are typically applied early in the season, when ascospores are first released.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] However, fungicide applications may also be made later in the season to prevent infection of old leaves, which can help reduce the amount of primary inoculum for the following season.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] To manage the development of fungicide resistance, growers can reduce the number of applications made throughout the season and alternate between different classes of fungicide.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] In organic production systems, growers commonly use copper- or sulfur-based protectant sprays to reduce the efficacy of primary inoculum.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Although these sprays were among the earliest methods of preventing the development of apple scab, they do little to manage pre-existing infections and application may significantly damage the foliage of treated trees.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Moreover, research has indicated that applications of copper-based fungicides may result in changes in the structure and functionality of soil microbiota, thus having a negative effect on soil health.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] As such, alternative management strategies appropriate for organic production systems are currently being developed.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Biological control refers to the use of a population of one organism (a biological control agent) to suppress the population of another.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] There are very few biological control agents registered for the control of apple scab.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] One of the most widely recognized products is Serenade® ASO, a microbial biofungicide which uses *Bacillus subtilis* as its active ingredient and may be used to control foliar diseases caused by bacteria or fungi.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Furthermore, several fungal antagonists have been isolated and identified as potential biocontrols.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] One of such antagonists is *Cladosporium cladosporioides* (strain H39).
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] This antagonistic fungus has demonstrated significant bioactivity against apple scab.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] This was indicated in a 2015 study, which found that applications of *C. cladosporioides* could reduce leaf scab incidence by 42–98% and apple scab incidence by 41–94% in both conventionally and organically managed orchards.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] The first formal resistance breeding programs for apple scab began in the early 20th century with the development of the PRI Apple Breeding Program by Purdue University, Rutgers University, and the University of Illinois.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Since its inception in 1945, the PRI Apple Breeding Program has used controlled crosses between cultivated apples and wild *Malus* species to develop 1500 resistant cultivars, 16 of which (including 'Prima,' 'Jonafree,' and 'Goldrush') have been named released into market.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Modern genetic work has found that a total of fifteen genes may confer resistance to apple scab.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Many of these genes have been isolated from wild *Malus* spp. populations in East Asia, where a high level of species diversity still remains.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Of these resistance genes, the Vf (Rvi6) gene is the most well-studied and is currently being used by researchers seeking to develop resistant cultivars using transgenic technology.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Another resistance gene is Va from Antonovka.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] While the development of transgenic resistant cultivars may reduce management costs in orchards, limited market acceptance pose a barrier to early adoption by commercial growers.
[src:apple-scab/apple-scab] Moreover, researchers have observed a breakdown of resistance genes by *Venturia* populations, posing another significant barrier to the success of this technology.
